Sprint 2 - Predicting Loan Grades¶

This is the continuation of the previous notebook. If this is the first file you are opening during correctiong, considering reviewing the readme file to understand how this project is structured.

In the previous files:

  • we have looked at our dataset: we have cleaned it and we have split our data into datasets for each of the sprints and tasks
  • we have created a model that can predict loan elegibility

In this file:

  • we will create a model that can predict loan grade.

This notebook begins with the same boilerplate as the other ones (imports, basic feature toggles, etc...)

Machine Learning¶

Predicting Loan Grade¶

For our next iteration, we want to predict loan grade.

For this iteration, we will not use the generated column we crafted (that was only needed for the first iteration).

Since the data cleaning and splitting are all done, this portion of the project (all the rest of them) will only require loading the right slice of data from disk!

This will be a lot more boring, so we will try to keep it light and focus on model performance instead of getting into detailed explanations. It's the same things we have done, with a bit more complexity (multiclass instead of binary classification)

Loading from cache [./cached/charts/grade_distribution_before_clustering.png]

We can see that we are trying to classify a very peculiar label.

  • multi-class: 7 distinct values
  • unbalanced: each with each own very distinct frequency
  • broad range of orders of magnitudes: undersampling to "G" level will not work

For this, we will reshape the data and try to build a simpler classifier:

  • A
  • B
  • C
  • D
  • X (the rest)

In [15]:
@cached_with_pickle()
def subsampled_hyper(X_hyper, y_hyper):
    min_sample = y_hyper[y_hyper == "X"].count()

    rus = RandomUnderSampler(
        sampling_strategy={
            "A": min_sample,
            "B": min_sample,
            "C": min_sample,
            "D": min_sample,
            "X": min_sample,
        },
        random_state=42,
    )
    X_hyper, y_hyper = rus.fit_resample(X_hyper, y_hyper)
    return X_hyper, y_hyper


X_hyper, y_hyper = subsampled_hyper(X_hyper, y_hyper)

def subsampled_train(X_train, y_train):

        sampling_strategy={

            "X": min_sample,
        },
        random_state=42,
    )
    X_train, y_train = rus.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
    return X_train, y_train

XGBClassifier (multi-class, single label)¶

In [20]:
def f1_score_micro(*args, **kwargs):
    score = f1_score(*args, **kwargs, average="micro")
    return score
In [23]:
def xgbclassifier_model_optimized():
    X = X_hyper
    y = y_hyper

    # we will set the target to "micro", but realistically, we don't care,
    # as our dataset is perfectly balanced after the undersampling.
    candi = optuna_utils.XgbClassifierCandidateProvider()
    study_name = f"sprint2_xgbclassifier_grade"
    optuna_utils.create_optuna_study(
        study_name=study_name, allow_resume=True, direction="maximize"
    )
    objective = optuna_utils.build_objective_function(
        candi, X, y, scoring_function=f1_score_micro
    )
    optuna_utils.parallelize_optuna(
        study_name, n_processes=1, trials_per_process=1, objective=objective
    )


if run_entire_notebook():
    xgbclassifier_model_optimized()

Decomposition and Scaling¶

These experiments are left here just for future reference, but most of them were scraped as the performance was MUCH worse after Scaling and decomposition (PCA() -> MinMaxScaler() ).

The entire log of the experiments and their performance can be found in the /optuna_studies/study_sprint2_xgbclassifier_grade_with_pca.db (along with many others combinations...). Some were so bad that got overwritten right afterwards. There was no value in even preserving their logs.

May this serve as a simple record for them:

  • PCA Only: 0.33
  • PCA + MinMax: 0.34
  • MinMax + PCA: 0.42
  • All of them well below the performance of the untouched data: 0.51

They have not been fully automated (pipelines/providers, etc..) because of the poor performance we got out of the box (too far below the original data to ever reach it/overtake it.)

In [48]:
def xgbclassifier_model_optimized_with_pca():
    X = X_hyper
    y = y_hyper
    minmax_X = MinMaxScaler().fit_transform(X)
    minmax_pca_X = minmax_X  # PCA(n_components=10).fit_transform(minmax_X)
    pca_y = y
    display(minmax_X)
    display(minmax_pca_X)
    display(pca_y)
    # we will set the target to "micro", but realistically, we don't care,
    # as our dataset is perfectly balanced after the undersampling.
    candi = optuna_utils.XgbClassifierCandidateProvider()
    study_name = f"sprint2_xgbclassifier_grade_with_minmax_only"
    optuna_utils.create_optuna_study(
        study_name=study_name, allow_resume=True, direction="maximize"
    )
    objective = optuna_utils.build_objective_function(
        candi, minmax_pca_X, pca_y, scoring_function=f1_score_micro
    )
    optuna_utils.parallelize_optuna(
        study_name, n_processes=15, trials_per_process=3, objective=objective
    )


if run_entire_notebook():
    xgbclassifier_model_optimized_with_pca()

experiments = [
    "sprint2_xgbclassifier_grade",
    "sprint2_logreg_grade",
    "sprint2_extra_trees_grade",
    "sprint2_random_forest_grade",
    "sprint2_xgbclassifier_grade_with_pca",
    "sprint2_xgbclassifier_grade_with_minmax_pca",
    "sprint2_xgbclassifier_grade_with_minmax_only",
]
scores = pd.DataFrame(
    [optuna_utils.get_study(name).best_value for name in experiments],
    index=experiments,
    columns=["f1_score"],
)
scores = scores.sort_values(by="f1_score", ascending=False)
scores["with transformations"] = 0
scores.loc[scores.index.str.contains("_with_"), "with transformations"] = 1
plt.xlim(0, 0.7)
sns.barplot(
    data=scores,
    y=scores.index,
    x="f1_score",
    hue=scores["with transformations"],
    dodge=False,
    palette=["#ff7d00", "#78290f"],
)
Out[51]:
<AxesSubplot: xlabel='f1_score'>

We can see that, in this specific dataset, performing dimensionality reduction and/or scaling, results in noticeably poorer predictive performance. There is important information captured by the diverging and different scales/magnitudes of the data.

It is also very interesting to see how big the performance improvement is, when we use scaling (after PCA)

The impact of scaling (scaling only) results in negligible performance drop..

Understanding our performance with yellowbrick¶

Just like before, since we used the hyperparameter split for tuning our model, we will see how well the model generalizes on unseen data. The "train" data split has never been seen by this tuned model, so it will serve us well, for now.

We expect to see similar performance as we saw during HP-tuning, indicating good generalizing behaviour (no specific overfitting to the hyperparamters decided during HP-tuning)

def sprint2_xgb_classifier_confusion_matrix():

    )
    cpe.fit(X_train_m, y_train_m)
    cpe.score(X_test_m, y_test_m)
    return cpe.show()

A meta analysis of Optuna trials & performance¶

In [84]:
@run
@cached_chart()
def optuna_trials_performance():
    trial_scores_completed = dict(
        map(
            lambda trial: [trial.number, trial.value]
            if trial.state == 1
            else [trial.number, None],
            optuna_utils.get_study("sprint2_xgbclassifier_grade").trials,
        )
    )
    trial_scores_all = dict(
        map(
            lambda trial: [trial.number, trial.value],
            optuna_utils.get_study("sprint2_xgbclassifier_grade").trials,
        )
    )
    sns.lineplot(trial_scores_completed)
    sns.scatterplot(trial_scores_all, color="red")
    sns.scatterplot(trial_scores_completed)
    plt.xlabel("iteration")
    plt.ylabel("f1_score")
    plt.ylim(0)
    plt.title("trial performance over time - completed vs pruned")
    return plt.gca()

A meta analysis of Optuna trials shows that most of the trials after the first 30/40 are only useful in refining/finely tuning the performance very marginally (from ~0.501 to ~0.503).. Probably not worth the effort to run hyper parameter tuning for too long (for this specific project!)

Lessons learned:

  • Windows-specific bugs: Spinning up subprocesses that spawn from Jupyter-managed Kernel is not supported and is a well known problem - see StackOverflow
    • Switching to using multiprocess instead of multiprocessing does allow us to spin subprocesses, but the way data, functions and data structures are serialized is cumbersome and makes our code harder to manage.
  • Logging and Exception Handling are no handled gracefully either and require manual workarounds (to even begin to detect what is causing the subprocesses to crash).
  • The apparent performance gain is negligible when we consider that most of the experiments "finish" early because they crash early... so not much gain in that sense...

Compare the performance to how well it works on Linux - slightly slower, but no crashes!
